Last year, the governor scored a major win against Mr Munya after ending a 17-year political enmity with Igembe North MP Maore Maoka.
However, Mr Kiraitu’s differences with Mr Aburi and Ms Mwangaza intensified the same year, leading to court battles and public spats.
The governor sued Mr Aburi on accusations of defaming him while Ms Mwangaza’s premises were raided by Meru County revenue officers on claims that she had failed to pay for various licences, allegations she denied.
But, speaking to the Nation on phone, Ms Mwangaza and Mr Aburi said they are not ready to settle their differences with the governor.
“My differences with the governor are not personal but due to lack of development. As long as the governor remains lazy without delivering development, I cannot be friends with him. When I asked questions about lack of development, they sent revenue officers to harass me,” Ms Mwangaza said.
Mr Aburi, who is also the National Ordinary People's Empowerment Union (Nopeu) party leader, said he would only meet Mr Kiraitu after “he leaves office in 2022”.
“Let the governor know that I am not ready to befriend him now. I am supporting Munya to unseat Kiraitu next year. I can only engage him when he is out of office in 2023. When we founded the Nopeu party, he was quick to dismiss us as a passing cloud,” Mr Aburi said.



